This Page shows the Weekly Trends for sales and profit over the course of a year (52 weeks). It helps you see when the business is doing well and when it’s struggling compared to its own average performance.

1. The Two Charts
Top Chart (Sales): Shows the total amount of money coming in each week. The average sales per week is about $14K (shown by the dotted horizontal line).

Bottom Chart (Profit): Shows how much money the business actually kept after expenses. The average profit per week is about $2K (shown by the dotted line).

2. The Color Code (The "KPI")
The lines change color based on whether the performance is "Above" or "Below" the average:

Blue Lines: The business performed better than average that week.

Orange Lines: The business performed worse than average that week.

3. Key Observations
End of Year Growth: Toward the end of the year (weeks 44–52), sales are consistently high and mostly blue, suggesting a strong "holiday" or year-end finish.

Profit Dips: Look at weeks 16–18 in the bottom chart. The line drops below the $0 mark, meaning the business actually lost money during those specific weeks, even though there were still sales happening.

Volatility: The jagged "staircase" shape (called a step chart) shows that business fluctuates significantly from one week to the next rather than staying steady.
